<sect1 id="headers-and-footers">
<title
>Headers/Footers</title>

<para
>With multi-page documents, you might want to provide certain
information at the tops or bottoms of each page throughout the document.
They can provide the reader with important information and they tie your
documents together. </para>

<para
>Fortunately, headers and footers are really just a special type of
frame.  You can edit the text and data within the headers and
footers</para>

<para
>You can toggle headers and footers independently at any
time.</para>

<para
>If you are using a Word processing template, the footers will be
added below the margins you set under page setup.  The text within the
main frames will be moved so the headers and/or footers do not overlap
any text.</para>

<para
>If you are using a <acronym
>DTP</acronym
> template, the
headers/footers will be placed at the margin edges, just like in the
word processing templates, but these frames are treated just like any
other frame.  If the text frame below the Header/footer frame is set to
wrap around text in overlapping frames, that will cause the text to
move.</para>

<para
>You can toggle the headers by selecting <menuchoice>
<guimenu
>View</guimenu
><guimenuitem
>Headers.</guimenuitem
></menuchoice>
from the Menu bar.</para>

<para
>You can toggle the footers by selecting <menuchoice>
<guimenu
>View</guimenu
><guimenuitem
>Footers.</guimenuitem
></menuchoice>
from the Menu bar.</para>

</sect1>

<sect1 id="template-creation">
<title
>Creating Templates/Saving a document as a template</title>

<para
>&kword; comes with several pre-defined templates (both
Word processing and <acronym
>DTP</acronym
> templates), which are designed
to get you started on your documents.</para>

<para
>If, however, you often use the same format for a document over and
over, you may want to create a template which
<emphasis
>exactly</emphasis
> matches your needs.</para>

<para
>You can create an unlimited number of templates in &kword;, and
you can organize them into categories for easy recall.</para>

<para
>You create these templates by first generating the layout in
&kword; based on one of the pre-defined templates, and then you save the
file.  Instead of saving it as a traditional file, you save it as a
template.</para>

<para
>What follows, is a step by step process to save the current
document as a template.</para>

<procedure>
<step>
<para
>When the document is like you want, Select <menuchoice>
<guimenu
>Extra</guimenu
><guimenuitem
>Create Template From
Document</guimenuitem
></menuchoice
> from the Menu bar.</para>

<para
>This brings up a dialog:</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject
><imagedata fileref="savetmpl1.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para
>This dialog helps you organize your templates into
categories.</para>
</step>

<step>
<para
>As you can see, your templates will be saved into a sub-directory
in your home directory.  You first need to create a Folder (which
represents a sub-directory) within the <filename
class="directory"
>templates</filename
> directory.</para>

<substeps>
<step>
<para
>To create this folder:</para>
<para
>Place the mouse cursor over the line directory name (in this
example: <filename
class="directory"
>/home/mmcbride/.kde/share/apps/kword/templates/</filename
>)
and click with the <mousebutton
>right</mousebutton
> mouse button.</para>

<para
>This will bring up a sub-menu.</para>
</step>
<step>
<para
>Select <guimenuitem
>Add Folder</guimenuitem
>.</para>

<para
>This will add another dialog to the screen.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="savetmpl2.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>
</step>
<step>
<para
>Type in a name for the folder.  The name should be descriptive of
the types of templates you will be placing within it.</para>
<para
>Click <guibutton
>Clear</guibutton
> to ???Not implemented yet???.</para>
<para
>Click <guibutton
>Cancel</guibutton
> to abort creating a new folder.</para>
<para
>Click <guibutton
>OK</guibutton
> to create this folder.</para>
<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject>
<imagedata fileref="savetmpl3.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>
<para
>The dialog box will now show your new folder.</para>
<note>
<para
>You do not need to create a new folder for each template.  The
folders you create can be used to organize your templates.</para>
<para
>You must, however, have at least one folder.  You can not save any
templates into the templates sub-directory.</para>
</note>
</step>
</substeps>
</step>
<step>
<para
>Select the newly created folder by clicking once on it with the
<mousebutton
>left</mousebutton
> mouse button.</para>
</step>

<step>
<para
>Type the name of your new template in the blank entitled
<guilabel
>Template Name</guilabel
>.</para>
</step>

<step>
<para
>You now need to select a graphic to represent your template in the
open document window.</para>
<para
>???Not implemented yet???</para
></step>
</procedure>

<para
>Once you have saved your template, the next time you open a
document, you will see your new category/new template in the open file
dialog.</para>

